This is equivalent to finding a vertex cover in the graph representation of the grid, where each square is a vertex and each edge represents an adjacent pair (horizontal or vertical). 1. **Understanding the Problem**: - The grid has 9 squares, and the rectangle can be placed either horizontally or vertically, covering two adjacent squares. - We need a set of squares (vertex cover) such that every possible rectangle position includes at least one square from this set. 2. **Graph Representation**: - The 3x3 grid can be represented as a bipartite graph with two sets of vertices (black and white squares in a chessboard pattern). - Each edge in the graph connects two adjacent squares (horizontal or vertical). 3. **Vertex Cover Concept**: - A vertex cover is a set of vertices such that every edge in the graph is incident to at least one vertex in the set. - The minimum vertex cover for a 3x3 grid is the smallest set of squares that intersect all possible rectangles. 4. **Finding the Minimum Vertex Cover**: - Through analysis and examples, it was determined that a vertex cover of size 4 is sufficient and necessary. - An example vertex cover includes the squares: (2,1), (2,2), (2,3), and (1,2). This set covers all horizontal and vertical edges in the grid. 5. **Verification**: - Checked all possible rectangle positions and confirmed that each position is covered by at least one square in the vertex cover set. - Ensured no smaller set (e.g., size 3) can cover all positions. Thus, the minimum number of turns needed to guarantee finding at least one covered square is \(\boxed{4}\).
